column12: Improvements in Devices or Means for Printing Writing Paper as it is Rolled Off a Reel.
column13: 23,095. Gamble, J. A. Oct. 18. Printing on mercantile forms, letter-sheets, etc.; rotary machines.-Relates to apparatus for printing headings on paper used for noting messages and orders at the telephone or counter or for invoices or receipt forms, of the type in which the paper from a roller after passing over the desk or writing-sur. face is wound on a receiving-drum. Near the paper roll A is a type wheel or cylinder B mounted on an axis C so as to rotate in contact with the paper on the roll A or with the paper that has been drawn off, in which case a wood roller is provided to receive the pressure of the type in printing. A spring may be provided to keep the type-wheel in contact with the paper. The type-wheel B is mounted on arms D pivoted at E, and a spring F forces the arm D upwards, so that the type-wheel B is in contact with the roll A. By turning the receiving-roll or pulling the free end of the paper G, the paper is wound off the roll A and the type-wheel is rotated. An inking-roll His mounted by a finger J on the arms D and is fitted with a spring I.- The type-wheel is provided at each end with ribs to prevent the type from indenting the paper.
column15: GAMBLE JOHN ALEXANDER

column12: Improvements in or connected with Apparatus for Recording Messages.
column13: 9338. Gamble, J. A. April 20. Telephones.-Improvements are made on the memorandum and duplicating appliances for use in connexion with telephones, described in Specifications No. 24,055, A.D. 1903, and No. 15,384, A.D. 1904. One improvement consists in the provision of piles of loose sheets f, f<1> on a baseboard e, which are pressed against the lid b of the box having openings c, d. A strip of paper h from the roller j passes over the top of one pile of the loose leaves f, and a sheet of carbon paper g serves for duplicating the writing thereon. In a modification, one of the piles of paper may be replaced by a rolled strip carried over a fixed writing-board k. In a further modification, the record strips may be rolls of paper placed in compartments without being mounted on spindles, and the papers may be pulled together over a writing-board at the top of the box, or a number of strips of paper may be wound on one roll.
column15: GAMBLE JOHN ALEXANDER

column12: Improvements in or relating to Apparatus in which Rolls of Paper or other Material are Wound or Unwound.
column13: 5874. Gamble, J. A. March 10. Mounting and securing paper and film rolls on shafts.-Relates to the mounting of paper rolls such as are used for recording telephone messages, cash receipts, &c. or of film rolls for cameras. To enable one spindle to be used many times for unwinding or winding a number of rolls, the roll A, Fig. 1, is wound on a cardboard &c. tube B, of greater diameter than the spindle C, and the tube B is preferably connected to the spindle by means of a metallic key E, which is driven into a groove in the spindle so as to jam itself between the tube and spindle and securely hold the tube. Another tube B similarly mounted may be provided, on which to wind up the paper. The spindle C is preferably provided with a detachable handle. To release the tube B from the spindle, the key E is driven out by a suitable tool. Instead of using the key E, the spindle C may be provided with a projection consisting of a piece of metal fixed to the spindle, and the tube B is in this case held to the spindle by forcing the spindle into the tube so as to cause the projection to embed itself in the tube.
column15: GAMBLE JOHN ALEXANDER

column12: Improvements in Devices for Recording or Registering Messages, Memoranda, and the like.
column13: 26,840. Gamble, J. A. Dec. 10. Memorandum appliances. - In a duplicating- appliance, in which one record is stored away and the other torn off, the two box-form parts of the casing are hinged together at the bottom at D, the meeting edges C of the parts being sloping. The back A<1> may be sloping or vertical and the appliance has rubber shoes B or may bang against a wall. The front part A is fastened by catches 2, and is open, being provided with a writing-surface H and a hinged metal cover-plate I in which are two rectangular openings separated by a springy bar S hinged at T and having a cutting-edge R. Turning a milled head K<1> on the axle K of the winding-reel causes the web E, guided at L, to carry the web G at the same pace across the table H, by means of a small pressure roller P mounted in the bar S. A milled head J<1> on the axle J permits movement of the paper in the reverse direction, if necessary. The axles J, K have shoulders at one end, and braking is provided by the edges C, and springs, pressing on the axles. Cutter members X, to start the cutting of the web G, are attached to the cover-plate I, which is cut and bent down at Y and bent up at Z so as to deflect the web G on to the top of the cover-plate. The stationary carbon sheet 0 is held at the lower opening under the edges of the cover-plate, by strips V, Fig. 5, hinged on canvas and fitting into grooves W in which the edges of the carbon sheet are clipped. The Provisional Specification also states that at the top of the case may be placed a spring-controlled roller carrying a web which bears telephone numbers &c., and springs back into a case when. not required.
column15: GAMBLE JOHN ALEXANDER

column12: Improvements in Continuous Sheet Writing Devices, adapted to give One or More Copies of Written Matter.
column13: 26,667. Gamble, J. A. Nov. 20. [Cognate Applications, 29,184/12 and 11,679/13.] Memorandum appliances. - In a continuoussheet writing-device for recording sales, an oddment space is provided above the feed-rollers for entering small amounts for which a bill is unnecessary, means being provided for unwinding the permanent record sheet without unwinding the bill sheets. For this purpose, the gripping rollers may be mounted so that they are normally in inoperative position and can be readily displaced, for example by pressure of the hand, into operative position, whereupon the bill and record sheets are unwound simultaneously. An advertising - device is provided comprising an endless band adapted to be moved and illuminated on the completion of each entry. The sheets are fed from rolls 7, 8, 9, Fig. 2, and are led over a writing-table 75, which is mounted by pins 77 thereon working in slots in springs 76 and rests on springs 74. The sheets are led between gripping-rollers 18, 19, the permanent record sheet 7 being wound on a crank-operated roll 10. The upper gripping-roller 19 is mounted on a transverse vertically-movable frame 28 carrying a knife 20 and provided with slots engaging fixed pins on the frame. Oddments are entered through a space 30 in a transparent cover 29 of glass, or of celluloid, in which case ears resting between the sheets, and the side pieces forming an angle flange to the casing, are formed integrally therewith. A space 31 is provided for cash summary statements. The axles of the rolls are mounted in grooves 25, 26, 27, being retained in position by means of rods 11 screwing into a plate 10. The carbon papers are held in position by means of a three-sided frame which can be locked on to the casing and covers the edges of the sheets. It is provided with pieces of rubber for gripping the carbon papers and with open slots in its vertical flanges engaging fixed pins. The advertising device consists of an endless band 50 exhibited through a window 56 and illuminated by a lamp 46. A bell-crank lever for releasing the cash drawer moves the band by means of a string wound on a helical groove on a roller 42 provided with a ratchet-wheel and pawl for preventing back motion. Simultaneously, the bell - crank lever closes suitable contacts, and the band is illuminated. The illumination of the lamp may be effected by the movement of the upper gripping- roller or the knife. A hand-rest sliding on side tracks may be provided.
column15: GAMBLE JOHN ALEXANDER

column12: Improvements in or relating to Memorandum and like Appliances for use in connection with Telephones and for other purposes.
column13: 24,055. Gamble, J. A. Nov. 5. Telephone station apparatus for indicating subscribers' names and other information.-Memorandum appliances for use in connection with telephones and for other purposes comprise two pairs of drums, the one pair feeding paper for writing upon and the other pair having a roll of paper bearing the names and numbers of telephone subscribers, or other information. The paper A, Fig. 2, in its passage between the two drums B, C passes over rollers c and a plain surface D in front of the opening in the casing E. The drums B, C are normally prevented from being turned backwards by the ratchet-wheels M and pawls L, which latter can be put out of action when desired. In order that the drums may be removable, the shank G, Fig. 5, of the milled heads F has a clutch H for engaging with the flanged stud 0 at the end of the drum. Longitudinal movement of the heads F is prevented by the grooves g in the shanks G engaging in slots in a sliding plate I, Fig. 3, which can be moved so that the heads F may be disengaged from the drums. The studs O and pins P are mounted in springy plates J to facilitate removal of the drums. The paper U passing over the drums S, T is divided into columns to receive the names of customers, with their telephone numbers &c. The drums are enclosed in a casing provided with a number of sliding doors V, by which any column can be exposed to view.
column15: GAMBLE JOHN ALEXANDER

column12: Improvements in or relating to Memorandum and like Appliances for use in connection with Telephones and for other purposes.
column13: 15,384. Gamble, J. A. July 9. Telephones.-Relates to memorandum and duplicating appliances for use in connection with telephones, being an improvement on the invention described in Specification No. 24,055, A.D. 1903. According to that Specification, a strip A of paper is wound over two drums B, C passed over a plain board forming a bard surface for writing on. These drums are now provided with ratchet-wheels and pawls and are normally prevented from moving longitudinally by a laterally-moving plate provided with slots engaging with grooves on the axles. On sliding this plate to one side, the drums can be drawn out and refilled. The drum C is locked in one direction by its ratchet-wheel M and pawl L, while on the other end of the drum B a similar ratchet-wheel and pawl locks the drum in the other direction, preventing any movement of the paper. By means of the lever 3 and the cam 4, either pawl may be disengaged and the drums rotated in either direction. For duplicating purposes, an additional "window" e<2> through which the paper is exposed is provided, and beneath the paper A passes the carbon paper X from the roll Y and the "copy" paper A<1> from the roll W. The axis w of this roll is held in two slots by springs so as to be readily removed and refilled. The knife-edge 2 is provided on the edge of the lid.
column15: GAMBLE JOHN ALEXANDER

column12: Improvements in or relating to Waterproof Devices or Apparatus for Protecting the Lower Limbs of Passengers, or the Seats, when Unoccupied, on the Outside of Vehicles from the Weather.
column13: 22,021. Gamble, J. A. Nov. 3. Aprons and seat protectors.-Fig. 1 shows the application to seats with reversible hollow backs. Guided aprons C are attached to spring rollers D, and passed down through the hollow space F and slits s, the beaded edges c preventing the springs from drawing the aprons entirely within the seat backs. The apron, which may have front and side flaps K, C', is withdrawn from its casing by pulling the edge c, and may be used to keep unoccupied seats dry by securing it to the seat at J. Holes are cut in the hollow back for drying and ventilating the aprons. In a modification, the apron comprises two sheets wound upon rollers fitted in a casing on the frame of the seat. Aprons of this construction may be fitted to vehicles having knifeboard seats, the spring rollers being fitted at the tops of hollow casings forming the sides of the vehicles.
column15: GAMBLE JOHN ALEXANDER

column12: Improvements in Indicating Devices for Tramcars, Railway Carriages and the like.
column13: 18,340. Gamble, J. A. Sept. 13. Indicators, station, stopping-place, and like; indicators, departure and arrival. -Relates to indicators for showing the names of stations or stopping- places, or other information, on omnibuses, tramcars, railway carriages, &c. The indicators may also be employed on the departure platforms of railway stations, for showing a list of the stopping- stations, and, if desired, the times at which the next train will stop. The names of the stations &c. are printed on a sheet of paper A, one side of which bears the names for the outward journey, and the other side the names for the return journey. The sheet A is mounted on and attached to the two drums B, C, as shown in Fig. 4, so that the indications for the outward and return journeys can be seen through the sight-apertures H, I respectively. The drums are rotated by the gearing F, E, D, L, M, from the hand-lever K, a small tell-tale indicator J being provided in the view of the operator. Stops N may be provided to engage in holes in the plate 0, to indicate the required extent of movement of the lever K for changing the indications, and a bell may be rang at each change. A shutter P is arranged in conjunction with the apertures H, I, to open the aperture for showing the desired indications, and to close the other aperture. The shutter is connected by the hinged arm R to the disc S which is loose on the shaft T, but has a frictional connection therewith through springs engaging the shaft, this arrangement effecting the movement of the shutter when the movement of the lever K is reversed.

column12: A METHOD OF MODULATING ENDOTHELIAL CELL ACTIVITY
column13: The present invention relates generally to a method of modulating endothelial cell activity and to agents useful for same. More particularly, the present invention relates to a method of modulating intercellular vascular endothelial permeability by modulating an intracellular protein kinase C-dependent signalling mechanism. The method for the present invention is useful, inter alia, in the treatment and/or prophylaxis of a condition characterised by aberrant, unwanted or otherwise inappropriate endothelial cell activity, in particular, conditions characterised by a loss of vascular integrity.

column12: CONTROL SYSTEM AND METHOD USING MULTIPLE INPUTS FOR CONTROLLING COOLING FAN SPEED OF OUTDOOR POWER EQUIPMENT UNIT
column13: An outdoor unit has a frame that carries a ground grooming or working implement, a traction drive, and a cooling fan, all of which comprises loads on a prime mover. A power management controller automatically reduces an operational speed of the traction drive when prime mover droop is present. The cooling fan cools two cooling fluids. The controller stores data representing variable fan speeds for cooling each cooling fluid in both normal and above normal temperature ranges and for use when prime mover droop is present. The controller uses the highest fan speed required for cooling the cooling fluids in the normal range unless the droop fan speed is lower in which case the lower droop fan speed is used but only to the extent that the lower droop fan speed is not lower than the highest fan speed required for cooling the cooling fluids in the above normal temperature range.

column12: Music management system
column13: A digital music system according to the present disclosure is a single processor system with a drag and drop interface that permits different digital content to be performed simultaneously in two or more performance zones. The user interface may be further optimized for use with a touchscreen display. Each performance zone may have a performance queue independent of other performance zones. Performance queues may be altered at any time during a performance. Transition between each item of digital content in a performance queue is accomplished using a crossfade with user-defined parameters. Additionally, a user in either performance zone may identify a digital content item for preview and the preview may be accomplished while the music management system is performing digital content in the two or more zones.
column15: ALEXANDER JIM;;GAMBLE KELLY;;WEAVER MIKE;;BEN-ZVY DORON

column12: OUTDOOR POWER EQUIPMENT UNIT WITH CONDITION RESPONSIVE ELECTRONIC CONTROL OF TRACTION DRIVE SYSTEM
column13: An outdoor power equipment unit comprises a self-propelled mower having a hydraulic traction drive system. When engine load exceeds a predetermined percentage of full load, a controller automatically reduces the stroke of a variable displacement pump in the traction drive system to reduce the ground speed of the mower without the operator having to change the position of the traction pedal. This reduces engine load to enhance continued good cutting performance. At any time, the controller can take the same actions to reduce ground speed if an excessively high temperature in a fluid used in a cooling system on the mower is detected, or if excessive loads on the mower decks of the mower are detected, or both.

column12: DNA sequences for human angiogenesis genes
column13: A nucleic acid molecule having the sequence of SEQ ID NO:1 and a polypeptide with the sequence of SEQ ID NO:115 are described. The nucleic acid and polypeptide play a role in diseases associated with angiogenesis. Modulators of expression or activity of the polypeptide and nucleic acids can be used in the manufacture of a medicament for the treatment of angiogenesis related disorders, such as cancer, rheumatoid arthritis, diabetic retinopathy, psoriasis, and atherosclerosis. Also described are antibodies, methods of diagnosis, methods for screening candidate pharmaceutical compounds and non-human transgenic animals.

column12: DNA sequences for human angiogenesis genes
column13: Novel nucleic acid sequences and encoded polypeptides involved in the process of angiogenesis are provided. In particular, provided are a BNO69 nucleic acid of SEQ ID NO: 1 and a BNO69 polypeptide of SEQ ID NO: 115. Methods are provided for treating subjects having pathologies associated with angiogenesis and for the screening of drugs for pro- or anti-angiogenic activity.

column12: DNA SEQUENCE FOR HUMAN ANGIOGENESIS GENE
column13:
PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide an isolated nucleic acid molecule for treatment of angiogenesis relating disorders.

SOLUTION: There are provided an isolated nucleic acid molecule containing a designated sequence in specific sequences; an isolated nucleic acid molecule hybridizing under a stringent condition with a nucleic acid molecule encoding a polypeptide playing a role in an angiogenic process and containing a nucleotide sequence in specific sequences; and the isolated nucleic acid molecule described above and encoding a polypeptide playing a role in angiogenesis-relating diseases including (not restricted thereto) cancers, rheumatoid arthritis, diabetic retinopathy, psoriasis, atherosclerosis, ischemic diseases of limbs, and cardiovascular diseases such as coronary diseases.

column12: A METHOD OF MODULATING CELLULAR TRANSMIGRATION AND AGENTS FOR USE THEREIN
column13: The present invention relates generally to a method of modulating cellular transendothelial migration and to agents useful for same. More particularly, the present invention relates to a method of modulating leukocyte extravasation by modulating an endothelial cell intracellular ERK (extracellular regulated kinase)-dependent signalling mechanism. The method of the present invention is useful, inter alia, in the treatment and/or prophylaxis of conditions characterised by aberrant, unwanted or otherwise inappropriate transendothelial cells migration, in particular, inflammatory conditions which are characterised by inappropriate leukocyte and, in particular, neutrophil transendothelial migration.

column12: PUSHER BIN FOR STORING BULK PRODUCTS
column13: Bins for storing a plurality of products includes a frame having an open top and a bottom, a product supporting platform movably coupled relative to the frame and configured to support the products thereon, a plurality of resilient members coupled relative to the frame and the platform, a plurality of pulleys coupled relative to the frame and the resilient members, and one or more line segments interconnecting the pulleys and coupled relative to the platform. The resilient members, the pulleys, and the one or more lines are arranged to cause each of the corners of the platform to simultaneously move in a direction toward the bottom of the frame in response to weight exerted by the products when the products are loaded onto the platform and in a direction toward the top of the frame in response to at least one of the products being picked from the platform.

column12: FAILSAFE SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR REDUCING LOAD IN A HYDRAULIC CYLINDER
column13: A mechanism to reduce load of a hydraulic cylinder having a body, a stem movable within the body, and a piston rod connected to the stem. The mechanism includes a mechanism body attached to the body and defining a recess, and a retainer attached to the mechanism adjacent the opening of the recess so that the retainer substantially fills the opening of the recess, and having an aperture that receives an end of the piston rod. The mechanism further includes a cap attached to the piston rod of the hydraulic cylinder within the recess, the cap having a diameter greater than the diameter of the aperture in the retainer, and a spring connected to the cap at a first end and to the retainer at a second end so that as the piston rod moves relative to the failsafe mechanism body, to reduce load transfer between the piston rod and the cylinder body.

column12: SEMICONDUCTOR-SUPERCONDUCTOR HYBRID DEVICE HAVING SIDE JUNCTIONS
column13: A semiconductor-superconductor hybrid device (400) comprises a semiconductor component (420) configured to host a 2DEG or a 2DHG; a superconductor component (430) for inducing superconductivity in a channel of the semiconductor component; and a set of depletion gates (452, 545, 456). The superconductor component comprises a grounded strip of superconductor. The depletion gates comprise a first outer gate (452 a, 452 b) for defining a first outer segment of the channel; a second outer gate (456 a, 456b) for defining a second outer segment of the channel; and an inner gate (454 a, 454 b) for defining an inner segment of the channel. The device further comprises a first junction comprising a space between the first outer gate and the inner gate, and a helper gate (470 a) for gating the first space; and a second junction comprising a space between the second outer gate and the inner gate, and a helper gate (470 b) for gating the second space. The helper gates are operable to connect the channel to leads (472 a, 472 b).

column12: Enhanced high temperature coated superconductors
column13:
This invention relates to a practical superconducting conductor based upon biaxially textured high temperature superconducting coatings. In particular, methods for producing flexible and bend strain-resistant articles and articles produced in accordance therewith are described which provide improved current sharing, lower hysteretic losses under alternating current conditions, enhanced electrical and thermal stability and improved mechanical properties between otherwise isolated films in a coated high temperature superconducting (HTS) wire. Multilayered materials including operational material which is sensitive to bend strain can be constructed, in which the bend strain in the region in which such operational material is located is minimized. The invention also provides a means for splicing coated tape segments and for termination of coated tape stack ups or conductor elements. 

   In one embodiment, a multi-layer high temperature superconductor is provided and includes first and second high temperature superconductor coated elements. Each element includes a substrate, at least one buffer deposited on the substrate, a high temperature superconductor layer, and a cap layer. The first and second high temperature superconductor coated elements are joined at the first and second cap layers.

column12: ENHANCED HIGH TEMPERATURE COATED SUPERCONDUCTORS
column13: This invention relates to a practical superconducting conductor based upon biaxially textured high temperature superconducting coatings. In particular, methods for producing flexible and bend strain-resistant articles and articl es produced in accordance therewith are described which provide improved curren t sharing, lower hysteretic losses under alternating current conditions, enhanced electrical and thermal stability and improved mechanical properties between otherwise isolated films in a coated high temperature superconductin g (HTS) wire. Multilayered materials including operational material which is sensitive to bend strain can be constructed, in which the bend strain in the region in which such operational material is located is minimized. The invention also provides a means for splicing coated tape segments and for termination of coated tape stack ups or conductor elements. In one embodimen t, a multi-layer high temperature superconductor is provided and includes first and second high temperature superconductor coated tape elements (11a, 11b). Each element includes s substrate (12a, 12b), at least one buffer (14a, 14b) deposited on the substrate, a high temperature superconductor layer (16a, 16 b) and a metallic cap layer (18a, 18b). The first and second high temperature superconductorcoated elements are joined at the first and second cap layers using soldering, diffusion bounding or the like.

column12: JOINT HIGH TEMPERATURE SUPERCONDUCTING COATED TAPES
column13: This invention relates to a practical superconducting conductor based upon biaxially textured high temperature superconducting coatings. In particular, methods for producing flexible and bend strain-resistant articles and articles produced in accordance therewith are described which provide improved current sharing, lower hysteretic losses under alternating current conditions, enhanced electrical and thermal stability and improved mechanical properties between otherwise isolated films in a coated high temperature superconducting (HTS) wire. Multilayered materials including operational material which is sensitive to bend strain can be constructed, in which the bend strain in the region in which such operational material is located is minimized. The invention also provides a means for splicing coated tape segments and for termination of coated tape stack ups or conductor elements. In one embodiment, a multi-layer high temperature superconductor is provided and includes first and second high temperature superconductor coated tape elements (11a, 11b). Each element includes s substrate (12a, 12b), at least one buffer (14a, 14b) deposited on the substrate, a high temperature superconductor layer (16a, 16b) and a metallic cap layer (18a, 18b). The first and second high temperature superconductor coated elements are joined at the first and second cap layers using soldering, diffusion bounding or the like.

column12: Authenticating interface element interactions
column13: An access control system is provided for preventing implicit granting access to privacy-related functions on an electronic device. Software-based events that grant access to device functions may be verified by confirming that the software event corresponds to a hardware input event. The verification prevents replacement of user interface inputs that can be used to fraudulently grant access to a particular function.
